>

  <!-- ─── Quick Answer ─── -->
  <QuickAnswerBox id="quick-answer">
    <p>
      <strong>kW (kilowatt)</strong> = real power actually doing useful work (running your appliances).
      <strong>kVA (kilovolt-ampere)</strong> = apparent power — what the electrical supply must provide,
      including "wasted" reactive power. <strong>kWh (kilowatt-hour)</strong> = energy consumed over time —
      this is what your electricity bill measures. The bridge between kW and kVA is the
      <strong>Power Factor (PF)</strong>: <code>kW = kVA × PF</code>.
      A 5 kVA generator at 0.8 PF delivers only <strong>4 kW</strong> of usable power.
    </p>
  </QuickAnswerBox>

  <!-- ─── Visual Explanation ─── -->
  <h2 id="visual-explanation">The Beer Mug Analogy — Understanding kW, kVA, and Reactive Power</h2>

  <p>
    The easiest way to understand these three terms is through the classic "beer mug" analogy used
    by electrical engineers worldwide:
  </p>

  <div class="example-box">
    <p class="example-label">The Beer Mug Analogy</p>
    <p>
      Imagine pouring beer into a tall mug. You get two things in the mug:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        🍺 <strong>The liquid beer</strong> = <strong>kW (Real Power)</strong> — this is what you actually
        wanted and what does the work. It runs your motors, lights, and appliances.
      </li>
      <li>
        🫧 <strong>The foam on top</strong> = <strong>Reactive Power (kVAR)</strong> — this is wasteful.
        It's generated by inductive loads (motors, transformers, compressors) and does no useful work,
        but the electrical supply has to accommodate it.
      </li>
      <li>
        🥛 <strong>The total contents of the mug</strong> = <strong>kVA (Apparent Power)</strong> — beer
        plus foam combined. Your generator, transformer, and supply cables must be sized to handle
        this total, even though only the beer fraction is useful.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      The ratio of beer to total contents is the <strong>Power Factor</strong>: a mug that's 80% beer
      and 20% foam has a power factor of 0.80. A perfectly filled mug (100% beer, 0% foam) would have
      a power factor of 1.0 — perfectly efficient but rarely achieved in practice.
    </p>
  </div>

  <p>
    In practical terms: <strong>resistive loads</strong> like electric heaters, incandescent bulbs, and
    ovens have a power factor of 1.0 (pure beer — no foam). <strong>Inductive loads</strong> like AC
    compressors, ceiling fan motors, refrigerators, and pumps have power factors of 0.7–0.9. This is
    why generators and UPS systems are always rated in kVA — they must supply both the useful kW and
    the reactive kVAR that motors demand.
  </p>

  <!-- ─── Step-by-Step ─── -->
  <h2 id="step-by-step">Step-by-Step: Converting Between kW, kVA, and kWh</h2>

  <div class="step-card">
    <div class="step-number">1</div>
    <div>
      <strong>kW → kVA (to size your generator or UPS)</strong>
      <p>
        Formula: <code>kVA = kW ÷ Power Factor</code>
        <br />
        Example: Your load is 3.5 kW with a typical home PF of 0.85.
        <br />
        Required kVA = 3.5 ÷ 0.85 = <strong>4.12 kVA</strong>.
        Choose the next standard generator size: a <strong>5 kVA generator</strong>.
        This gives a 20% safety headroom, which is recommended.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="step-card">
    <div class="step-number">2</div>
    <div>
      <strong>kVA → kW (to find usable power from a generator)</strong>
      <p>
        Formula: <code>kW = kVA × Power Factor</code>
        <br />
        Example: You have a 7.5 kVA generator and the manufacturer specifies PF = 0.8.
        <br />
        Usable real power = 7.5 × 0.8 = <strong>6 kW</strong>.
        You can run appliances totalling up to 6,000W safely.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="step-card">
    <div class="step-number">3</div>
    <div>
      <strong>kW → kWh (to calculate energy consumed / units on bill)</strong>
      <p>
        Formula: <code>kWh = kW × Hours</code>
        <br />
        Example: A 2 kW load (two 1 Ton ACs) running for 6 hours.
        <br />
        Energy consumed = 2 kW × 6 hours = <strong>12 kWh = 12 units</strong>.
        At ₹6/unit, that's ₹72 for one day of AC usage.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="step-card">
    <div class="step-number">4</div>
    <div>
      <strong>kWh → kW (to find average load from a bill)</strong>
      <p>
        Formula: <code>kW = kWh ÷ Hours</code>
        <br />
        Example: Your bill shows 300 kWh consumed over 30 days.
        <br />
        Assuming 10 hours of active use per day: Average load = 300 ÷ (30 × 10) = <strong>1 kW average</strong>.
        This helps you understand typical load behaviour and right-size an inverter.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="step-card">
    <div class="step-number">5</div>
    <div>
      <strong>Finding Power Factor from kW and kVA</strong>
      <p>
        Formula: <code>PF = kW ÷ kVA</code>
        <br />
        Example: A UPS spec says it provides 1 kVA output and the load is 850W (0.85 kW).
        <br />
        Power Factor = 0.85 ÷ 1.0 = <strong>0.85</strong>.
        This UPS is operating at a healthy power factor — right in the typical residential range.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ─── Real Example ─── -->
  <h2 id="real-example">Real Example: Sizing a Generator for Your Home</h2>

  <div class="example-box">
    <p class="example-label">Scenario — Generator for a 2 BHK Home During Power Cut</p>
    <p>
      You want to run the following appliances during a power cut: 1 × 1.5 Ton AC, 4 × ceiling fans,
      6 × LED bulbs, 1 × refrigerator, and 1 × TV.
    </p>

    <p><strong>Step 1: Add up the watts</strong></p>
    <ul>
      <li>1.5 Ton AC: 1,600W</li>
      <li>4 × Ceiling Fan (75W): 300W</li>
      <li>6 × LED Bulb (10W): 60W</li>
      <li>Refrigerator: 200W</li>
      <li>TV (40"): 90W</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Total: 2,250W = 2.25 kW</strong></p>

    <p><strong>Step 2: Convert kW → kVA</strong></p>
    <p>
      Mixed home load (fans + AC + compressors) has a typical PF of about 0.80–0.85.
      Using PF = 0.82: Required kVA = 2.25 ÷ 0.82 = <strong>2.74 kVA</strong>
    </p>

    <p><strong>Step 3: Add 20% safety headroom</strong></p>
    <p>
      2.74 × 1.20 = <strong>3.29 kVA</strong> minimum generator size.
    </p>

    <p><strong>Step 4: Choose from standard sizes</strong></p>
    <p>
      Common generator sizes: 2 kVA, 3 kVA, <strong>3.5 kVA</strong>, 5 kVA, 7.5 kVA, 10 kVA.
      → Choose a <strong>3.5 kVA generator</strong> (adequate with some headroom) or a <strong>5 kVA</strong>
      if you want comfort margin for future additions or motor starting surges.
    </p>

    <p><strong>Why does the AC motor matter?</strong></p>
    <p>
      AC compressors draw 3–5× their running current for the first few seconds on startup (inrush current).
      A 1,600W AC might briefly demand 5,000–7,000W during startup. Generators with "surge capacity" ratings
      handle this; always check the generator's peak surge power spec alongside its continuous kVA rating.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Verdict:</strong> A <strong>5 kVA generator</strong> (4 kW real power at 0.8 PF) is the
      comfortable, reliable choice for this home. It handles the AC startup surge and allows some headroom
      for additional small loads.
    </p>
  </div>

  <!-- ─── Reference Table ─── -->
  <h2 id="reference-table">Quick Reference Table: kW vs kVA vs kWh</h2>

  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
