          <td>Small UPS ratings (home inverters)</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <p>
    <strong>Typical Power Factor values in Indian homes:</strong>
  </p>

  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Load Type</th>
          <th>Typical Power Factor</th>
          <th>Examples</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Purely resistive</td>
          <td>1.0</td>
          <td>Electric heater, incandescent bulb, geyser</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>LED lighting</td>
          <td>0.90–0.95</td>
          <td>Quality LED bulbs and tube lights</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Ceiling fans</td>
          <td>0.70–0.85</td>
          <td>Standard induction motor fans</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Refrigerator</td>
          <td>0.75–0.85</td>
          <td>Compressor-based cooling</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>AC (non-inverter)</td>
          <td>0.75–0.85</td>
          <td>Fixed-speed compressor ACs</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>AC (inverter type)</td>
          <td>0.85–0.95</td>
          <td>Variable-speed inverter ACs</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Mixed home load</td>
          <td>0.80–0.85</td>
          <td>Typical residential mixture</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Industrial motors</td>
          <td>0.70–0.85</td>
          <td>Large 3-phase induction motors</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <!-- ─── Common Mistakes ─── -->
  <h2 id="common-mistakes">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

  <div class="mistake-card">
    <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="w-5 h-5 text-danger flex-shrink-0" aria-hidden="true"><path d="m21.73 18-8-14a2 2 0 0 0-3.48 0l-8 14A2 2 0 0 0 4 21h16a2 2 0 0 0 1.73-3Z" /><line x1="12" y1="9" x2="12" y2="13" /><line x1="12" y1="17" x2="12.01" y2="17" /></svg>
    <div>
      <strong>Using kVA and kW interchangeably</strong>
      <p style="margin:0.25rem 0 0;font-size:0.875rem;color:var(--text-muted);">
        This is the most common mistake. A "5 kVA generator" does NOT mean you can run 5 kW of appliances.
        At a typical PF of 0.8, it delivers only 4 kW. Ignoring this means you'll overload your generator,
        causing it to cut out under load or damage your appliances. Always ask for both kVA and kW ratings
        when shopping for generators and UPS systems.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="mistake-card">
    <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="w-5 h-5 text-danger flex-shrink-0" aria-hidden="true"><path d="m21.73 18-8-14a2 2 0 0 0-3.48 0l-8 14A2 2 0 0 0 4 21h16a2 2 0 0 0 1.73-3Z" /><line x1="12" y1="9" x2="12" y2="13" /><line x1="12" y1="17" x2="12.01" y2="17" /></svg>
    <div>
      <strong>Confusing kWh with kW on your electricity bill</strong>
      <p style="margin:0.25rem 0 0;font-size:0.875rem;color:var(--text-muted);">
        Your bill shows consumption in kWh (units) — not kW. A common question is "My bill says 300 units —
        is that my load?" No — 300 kWh is the energy consumed over a billing period. Your actual load in kW
        depends on how many hours you used electricity. If you want to know your average load:
        Load (kW) = Bill Units ÷ (Days × Hours per day of use).
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="mistake-card">
    <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="w-5 h-5 text-danger flex-shrink-0" aria-hidden="true"><path d="m21.73 18-8-14a2 2 0 0 0-3.48 0l-8 14A2 2 0 0 0 4 21h16a2 2 0 0 0 1.73-3Z" /><line x1="12" y1="9" x2="12" y2="13" /><line x1="12" y1="17" x2="12.01" y2="17" /></svg>
    <div>
      <strong>Selecting inverter capacity in VA without checking power factor</strong>
      <p style="margin:0.25rem 0 0;font-size:0.875rem;color:var(--text-muted);">
        Home inverters (Luminous, Microtek, etc.) are sold by VA rating: 850VA, 1100VA, 1500VA, etc.
        But the usable watt capacity depends on the power factor. A 1,100 VA inverter at PF 0.8 can
        power only 880W of load. If you're running an AC along with fans and lights, calculate the total
        kVA required first, then choose the inverter with the next higher VA rating for safety margin.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="mistake-card">
    <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="w-5 h-5 text-danger flex-shrink-0" aria-hidden="true"><path d="m21.73 18-8-14a2 2 0 0 0-3.48 0l-8 14A2 2 0 0 0 4 21h16a2 2 0 0 0 1.73-3Z" /><line x1="12" y1="9" x2="12" y2="13" /><line x1="12" y1="17" x2="12.01" y2="17" /></svg>
    <div>
      <strong>Assuming power factor is always 1.0</strong>
      <p style="margin:0.25rem 0 0;font-size:0.875rem;color:var(--text-muted);">
        Every electrical formula without a power factor term is implicitly assuming PF = 1.0 — which
        is only true for purely resistive loads. The moment you have motors, compressors, or fluorescent
        ballasts, PF drops to 0.7–0.9. Always use PF = 0.85 as a conservative estimate for mixed
        residential loads when you don't have the exact value.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="mistake-card">
    <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="w-5 h-5 text-danger flex-shrink-0" aria-hidden="true"><path d="m21.73 18-8-14a2 2 0 0 0-3.48 0l-8 14A2 2 0 0 0 4 21h16a2 2 0 0 0 1.73-3Z" /><line x1="12" y1="9" x2="12" y2="13" /><line x1="12" y1="17" x2="12.01" y2="17" /></svg>
    <div>
      <strong>Thinking higher kVA always means better performance</strong>
      <p style="margin:0.25rem 0 0;font-size:0.875rem;color:var(--text-muted);">
        A 10 kVA generator with PF 0.7 gives only 7 kW — less usable power than an 8 kVA generator
        with PF 0.9 (7.2 kW). Look at the kW (real power) specification, not just the kVA headline.
        Premium generators and inverters advertise their kW output alongside kVA for this reason.
        Also check total harmonic distortion (THD%) for sensitive electronics.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

