  <!-- ─── FAQs ─── -->
  <h2 id="faqs">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

  <div class="kh-faq">
    <details>
      <summary>
        Why does my inverter shut down even though my load seems within its VA rating?
        <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="currentColor" class="faq-chevron w-4 h-4"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4.22 6.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L8 8.94l2.72-2.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-3.25 3.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0L4.22 7.28a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd" /></svg>
      </summary>
      <div class="faq-body">
        Most home inverters have both a VA (apparent power) limit and a watt (real power) limit —
        sometimes a third limit on peak current. If your load has a poor power factor (lots of motors),
        the inverter might hit its watt limit before the VA limit. Or, the startup surge of an AC
        compressor or pump may briefly exceed the peak current rating. Check your inverter's spec sheet
        for "rated output power in watts" separately from "VA rating." Also ensure the battery is
        fully charged — low battery voltage causes early shutdown even before rated load is reached.
      </div>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>
        What power factor should I use for sizing a home generator?
        <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="currentColor" class="faq-chevron w-4 h-4"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4.22 6.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L8 8.94l2.72-2.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-3.25 3.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0L4.22 7.28a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd" /></svg>
      </summary>
      <div class="faq-body">
        Use PF = 0.80 as a conservative default for a typical Indian home with a mix of ACs, fans,
        and lighting. If you have mostly resistive loads (geysers, heaters, irons) and LED lighting,
        you can use PF = 0.90. If you have many induction motors or an older non-inverter AC, use
        PF = 0.75 to be safe. Most generator manufacturers rate their machines at PF = 0.8, so a
        "5 kVA generator" is expected to deliver 4 kW at PF 0.8 — this is the standard assumption.
      </div>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>
        Is kWh the same as "units" on my electricity bill?
        <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="currentColor" class="faq-chevron w-4 h-4"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4.22 6.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L8 8.94l2.72-2.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-3.25 3.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0L4.22 7.28a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd" /></svg>
      </summary>
      <div class="faq-body">
        Yes — 1 kWh = 1 unit of electricity on your bill. "Unit" is the colloquial Indian term for
        kilowatt-hour. Your electricity meter accumulates kWh and your DISCOM bills you per unit consumed
        in the billing period. If you consume 250 units in a month, that means 250 kWh of energy was
        drawn from the grid.
      </div>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>
        Can a poor power factor increase my electricity bill?
        <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="currentColor" class="faq-chevron w-4 h-4"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4.22 6.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L8 8.94l2.72-2.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-3.25 3.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0L4.22 7.28a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd" /></svg>
      </summary>
      <div class="faq-body">
        For residential consumers in India, most DISCOMs bill purely on kWh consumed — the meter measures
        active energy only, so poor PF doesn't directly increase your per-unit bill. However, poor PF
        causes higher current to flow through your home wiring for the same real power, leading to more
        resistive heating losses in cables, potential nuisance tripping of MCBs, and faster aging of wires.
        For commercial and industrial consumers, most DISCOMs impose a "power factor surcharge" or penalty
        when PF drops below 0.85, making power factor correction economically significant at scale.
      </div>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>
        What is a good power factor for my home?
        <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="currentColor" class="faq-chevron w-4 h-4"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4.22 6.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L8 8.94l2.72-2.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-3.25 3.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0L4.22 7.28a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd" /></svg>
      </summary>
      <div class="faq-body">
        A power factor above 0.85 is considered good for residential applications. Modern inverter ACs,
        high-quality LED drivers, and inverter-type appliances have better built-in power factor correction
        (PFC) circuits and typically achieve 0.90–0.99 PF. Older non-inverter appliances, cheap LED bulbs,
        and induction motors without PFC tend to pull the household average down to 0.75–0.82.
        You don't need to obsess about PF at home — just be aware of it when sizing a generator or inverter.
      </div>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>
        How does kWh relate to CO₂ emissions and environmental impact?
        <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="currentColor" class="faq-chevron w-4 h-4"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4.22 6.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L8 8.94l2.72-2.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-3.25 3.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0L4.22 7.28a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd" /></svg>
      </summary>
      <div class="faq-body">
        In India, the current grid emission factor is approximately <strong>0.82 kg CO₂ per kWh</strong>
        (Central Electricity Authority, 2023). This means every 1 unit (kWh) of electricity you consume
        from the grid results in about 820 grams of CO₂ being emitted at the power plant level. A home
        consuming 300 units/month generates roughly 246 kg of CO₂ monthly — about 2.95 tonnes per year.
        Solar rooftop generation offsets this directly: 1 kWh of solar generated = 0.82 kg CO₂ avoided.
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

